    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-06-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-06-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="180"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d180">
                <head>180. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d180fn0"
                        >Source: Department of State, Conference Files: Lot 64 D 559, CF 1686.
                        Secret; Limit Distribution. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_KFD1"
                            >Kohler</persName> and approved in <gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss> on
                        June 3. See also <ref target="#d179">Document 179</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1960-06-02">June 2, 1960</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Tripartite Consultation</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Here follows the same list of participants as <ref target="#d179">Document
                        179</ref>.]</p>
                <p>The Secretary referred to the tripartite discussion at his house last night with
                    respect to tripartite consultation. He said he hoped in view of the conclusions
                    they had reached that it would be satisfactory for the President to go ahead and
                    reply to <persName corresp="#p_MH1">Macmillan</persName>’s letter of May 25<note
                        n="1" xml:id="d180fn1">
                        <ref target="#d177">Document 177</ref>.</note> without waiting for a
                    communication from General <persName corresp="#p_DEGC1">de Gaulle</persName>.
                        <persName corresp="#p_CMM1">Couve</persName> agreed that this would seem
                    satisfactory. He said <persName corresp="#p_DEGC1">de Gaulle</persName> would
                    probably also be replying to <persName corresp="#p_MH1">Macmillan</persName> and
                    at the same time write to President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName>.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CMM1">Couve</persName> then said he supposed that he would
                    meet the Secretary and <persName corresp="#p_LS1">Selwyn Lloyd</persName> again
                    in September in New York on the occasion of the opening of the <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">U.N.</gloss> General Assembly. He suggested and the
                    Secretary agreed that it would be relatively easy to arrange a further meeting
                    between the three in New York with a minimum of press pressure or publicity.</p>
            </div>
